<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="129" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,153,467]" pageId="7" pageNumber="129">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,153,179]" pageId="7" pageNumber="129">Remarks.</emphasis>
Although 
<bibRefCitation author="Takahashi, Y. &amp; Dick, M. H. &amp; Mawatari, S. F." box="[434,695,153,179]" pageId="7" pageNumber="129" pagination="61 - 79" refId="ref5809" refString="Takahashi, Y., Dick, M. H. &amp; Mawatari, S. F. (2007) Sea spiders (Arthropoda: Pycnogonida) from waters adjacent to the Nansei Islands of Japan. Journal of Natural History, 41, 61 - 79. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222930601121783" type="journal article" year="2007">
Takahashi 
<emphasis box="[555,605,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="129">et al</emphasis>
. (2007)
</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName box="[817,935,154,179]" class="Pycnogonida" family="Pycnogonidae" genus="Pycnogonum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pantopoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spatium">
<emphasis box="[817,935,154,179]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="129">P. spatium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as having granular integument, the body integument being pitted (
<figureCitation box="[410,497,189,215]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1297,1322]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,345,1272]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[177,1411,345,1272]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Integument. Pycnogonum (Nulloviger) granulatum sp. nov.; A–B. A, granulated integument of abdomen, dorsal view; B, granulated integument of femur, distal surface. P. spatium; C–D. C, pitted integument of abdomen, dorsal view; D, granulated and fitted integument of femur, distal surface. All images are observed under the light microscope (Olympus BX51, Japan). Scale bars: 0.1 mm (A, C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3702911" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3702911/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="129">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
), and only the dorsal surface of legs being granulated and pitted (
<figureCitation box="[1230,1320,189,215]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1297,1322]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,345,1272]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[177,1411,345,1272]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Integument. Pycnogonum (Nulloviger) granulatum sp. nov.; A–B. A, granulated integument of abdomen, dorsal view; B, granulated integument of femur, distal surface. P. spatium; C–D. C, pitted integument of abdomen, dorsal view; D, granulated and fitted integument of femur, distal surface. All images are observed under the light microscope (Olympus BX51, Japan). Scale bars: 0.1 mm (A, C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3702911" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3702911/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="129">Fig. 3D</figureCitation>
). The proboscis length was recorded as 
<quantity box="[492,595,225,251]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.699999999999999" pageId="7" pageNumber="129" unit="mm" value="0.47">0.47 mm</quantity>
, while it is actually 
<quantity box="[821,921,225,251]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.9" pageId="7" pageNumber="129" unit="mm" value="0.89">0.89 mm</quantity>
(
<figureCitation box="[936,1024,224,251]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1939,1964]" captionTargetBox="[225,1363,627,1913]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[225,1363,627,1913]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 5. Pycnogonum spatium, holotype.A, trunk, dorsal view; B, trunk, lateral view; C, trunk, anterodorsal view; D, third leg, long spine on femur broken; E, fourth leg, arrow indicating gonopore; F, second leg, arrow indicating coxal pellicula. Scale bars: 1 mm (A–B); 0.5 mm (C–D); 0.1 mm (E–F)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3702915" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3702915/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="129">Fig. 5B</figureCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Takahashi, Y. &amp; Dick, M. H. &amp; Mawatari, S. F." box="[1044,1303,225,251]" pageId="7" pageNumber="129" pagination="61 - 79" refId="ref5809" refString="Takahashi, Y., Dick, M. H. &amp; Mawatari, S. F. (2007) Sea spiders (Arthropoda: Pycnogonida) from waters adjacent to the Nansei Islands of Japan. Journal of Natural History, 41, 61 - 79. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222930601121783" type="journal article" year="2007">
Takahashi 
<emphasis box="[1165,1214,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="129">et al</emphasis>
. (2007)
</bibRefCitation>
determined the 
<taxonomicName box="[191,307,262,287]" class="Pycnogonida" family="Pycnogonidae" genus="Pycnogonum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pantopoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spatium">
<emphasis box="[191,307,262,287]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="129">P. spatium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<typeStatus box="[313,411,261,287]" pageId="7" pageNumber="129">holotype</typeStatus>
to be a female based on gonopores being on the dorsal surface of coxa 2 of all legs (
<figureCitation box="[1339,1422,260,287]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1939,1964]" captionTargetBox="[225,1363,627,1913]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[225,1363,627,1913]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 5. Pycnogonum spatium, holotype.A, trunk, dorsal view; B, trunk, lateral view; C, trunk, anterodorsal view; D, third leg, long spine on femur broken; E, fourth leg, arrow indicating gonopore; F, second leg, arrow indicating coxal pellicula. Scale bars: 1 mm (A–B); 0.5 mm (C–D); 0.1 mm (E–F)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3702915" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3702915/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="129">Fig. 5F</figureCitation>
), however the present observation reveals that there is a gonopore on the ventrodistal surface of coxa 2 on each fourth leg (
<figureCitation box="[201,287,332,359]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1939,1964]" captionTargetBox="[225,1363,627,1913]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[225,1363,627,1913]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 5. Pycnogonum spatium, holotype.A, trunk, dorsal view; B, trunk, lateral view; C, trunk, anterodorsal view; D, third leg, long spine on femur broken; E, fourth leg, arrow indicating gonopore; F, second leg, arrow indicating coxal pellicula. Scale bars: 1 mm (A–B); 0.5 mm (C–D); 0.1 mm (E–F)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3702915" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3702915/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="129">Fig. 5E</figureCitation>
), which shows the trait of a male. In this case, we can suggest two possibilities, the first being that the specimen is a hermaphrodite and secondly the female gonopores were misdiagnosed and represent coxal pelliculae (
<emphasis box="[161,208,405,431]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="129">vide</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Staples, D. A." box="[213,367,405,431]" pageId="7" pageNumber="129" pagination="79 - 94" refId="ref5442" refString="Staples, D. A. (2007) A new species of Colossendeis (Pycnogonida: Colossendeidae) together with records from Australian and New Zealand waters. Memoirs of Museum Victoria, 64, 79 - 94. https: // doi. org / 10.24199 / j. mmv. 2007.64.8" type="journal article" year="2007">Staples, 2007</bibRefCitation>
), in which case the specimen is a male belonging to the subgenus 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stock" baseAuthorityYear="1968" box="[1096,1216,405,431]" class="Pycnogonida" family="Pycnogonidae" genus="Pycnogonum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pantopoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Nulloviger">
<emphasis box="[1096,1216,405,431]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="129">Nulloviger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. To solve this problem, we need additional collection of specimens and research to distinguish the coxal pellicula from the gonopore.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
